        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.  He was nine, the air in Clarion Alley thick with the smell of spray paint and cheap beer. His mother, Elena, was on a ladder, adding a fiery gold to a sun in a community mural. His father stood beside him, explaining that this was history, too\u2014not in a dusty book, but alive on a wall for everyone to see. Marco touched the still-damp paint, feeling the city's pulse under his small hand. It was the first time he understood that justice wasn't just an idea; it was a color, a story, something you could create.\n\n2.  The fluorescent hum of the SF State library is a sound he can still recall with sickening clarity. He was reading a dense chapter on social policy when his phone buzzed. His t\u00eda\u2019s voice was a shattered thing, saying Javier\u2019s name, then the word fentanyl. The theories and statistics in the book turned to meaningless ash. All the academic language couldn't hold the weight of that one, hollowed-out moment. He walked out of the library that day and never went back; his real education had just begun.\n\n3.  His first winter working outreach in the Tenderloin, he spent an hour on a wet curb next to a girl half his age, shaking with withdrawal. He didn't preach or advise; he just sat with her in silence, offering a bottle of water. Finally, she met his eyes and whispered, \"Thanks for not looking away.\" In that moment, Marco felt a purpose so sharp and clear it eclipsed all his grief and doubt. He wasn\u2019t saving the world, just refusing to let one person be invisible. It was enough.\n\n4.  The last conversation with his long-term partner wasn't a fight at all. She was standing by the door of their Inner Richmond apartment, keys in hand, her face full of a quiet, settled sorrow. \"There\u2019s no room left for me, Marco,\" she\u2019d said. \"The city\u2019s pain\u2026 it takes up all the space.\" He couldn't argue, because he knew she was right. The silence after the door clicked shut was the price of his dedication, a personal grief he learned to carry alongside the city's.\n\n5.  Riding the 38-Geary last year, he saw a kid slumped in a doorway who had his cousin Javier\u2019s profile, and the familiar gut-punch of grief hit him. But then, a block later, he saw Maria\u2014one of his trainees\u2014calmly kneeling to offer Narcan to a man in crisis. The sight of her competence, of the compassion he\u2019d helped nurture, didn\u2019t erase his pain. But for the first time, it felt like a legacy, not just a wound. It was the reason he stayed."
